WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.400
[Amit Varma]: What is common to all human beings? Here's one answer. We are all mathematical modellers.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:14.460
[Amit Varma]: Think about it. Whenever you do something, you have a sense of how it will turn out.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:19.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is based on past experience and knowledge and so on. Like when you cross the road, you

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:22.840
[Amit Varma]: know that there's a tiny chance that you will be run over. But there is a model in your

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:27.600
[Amit Varma]: head that tells you that there's a high probability of getting to the other side. So off you go

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:32.980
[Amit Varma]: crossing the road along with the proverbial chicken. Now, while you're modelling the future,

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:37.320
[Amit Varma]: you're not explicitly modelling the future. You're not laying down all your assumptions,

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:42.240
[Amit Varma]: putting numbers to them, assigning probabilities, doing Bayesian thinking, none of that. But

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:47.800
[Amit Varma]: implicitly, you're doing a crude version of modelling. And it has always been my contention

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:53.240
[Amit Varma]: that refining this crude process in our heads can help us think clearly about the world.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:59.160
[Amit Varma]: It can make us more mindful about what we do and why. It can give us insight into ourselves.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:04.320
[Amit Varma]: What are our priorities? What are our biases? What are we in denial about? That is why for

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:08.880
[Amit Varma]: personal growth, if nothing else, we should think more about the modelling processes that

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:14.240
[Amit Varma]: we adopt. If we are not clear about why we are doing what we are doing, then isn't it

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:32.120
[Unknown]: much more likely that we'll make mistakes?

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:35.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Gautam Menon, a professor of physics

00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:41.720
[Amit Varma]: and biology at Ashoka University, and a pioneer in the relatively new field of biophysics.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:46.480
[Amit Varma]: Gautam is also a pioneer in the mathematical modelling of infectious diseases, and was

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:51.200
[Amit Varma]: one of the first specialists to take COVID-19 seriously before the pandemic hit last year.

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:55.520
[Amit Varma]: I have gotten tremendous insights from his scholarship and his public work over the last

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: few months, and I was delighted to have him as a guest on the show. As I expected, I got

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:05.520
